Phase 2 – Manual System Integrity and Malware Validation
Additional system validation performed.
Process inspection:
tasklist
Network inspection:
netstat -ano
No suspicious outbound connections observed.
Startup inspection executed using Sysinternals Autoruns.
Manual inspection locations:
Task Scheduler (taskschd.msc)
Services (services.msc)
Startup folders
Registry keys:
HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run
HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run
Result:
No persistence mechanisms detected.

Phase 3 – Windows Firewall Full Reconstruction
Default inbound block policy enforced:
Set-NetFirewallProfile -Profile Domain,Public,Private -DefaultInboundAction Block
Default outbound block policy enforced:
Set-NetFirewallProfile -Profile Domain,Public,Private -DefaultOutboundAction Block
Explicit inbound port blocks applied:
netsh advfirewall firewall add rule name="Block RDP DesktopII" dir=in action=block protocol=TCP localport=3389
netsh advfirewall firewall add rule name="Block SMB DesktopII" dir=in action=block protocol=TCP localport=445
netsh advfirewall firewall add rule name="Block RPC DesktopII" dir=in action=block protocol=TCP localport=135
netsh advfirewall firewall add rule name="Block NetBIOS DesktopII" dir=in action=block protocol=TCP localport=139
netsh advfirewall firewall add rule name="Block SSDP DesktopII" dir=in action=block protocol=UDP localport=1900
netsh advfirewall firewall add rule name="Block LLMNR DesktopII" dir=in action=block protocol=UDP localport=5355
Minimal outbound allow rules created:
New-NetFirewallRule -DisplayName "Allow HTTPS DesktopII" -Direction Outbound -Protocol TCP -RemotePort 443 -Action Allow
New-NetFirewallRule -DisplayName "Allow HTTP DesktopII" -Direction Outbound -Protocol TCP -RemotePort 80 -Action Allow
New-NetFirewallRule -DisplayName "Allow DNS DesktopII UDP" -Direction Outbound -Protocol UDP -RemotePort 53 -Action Allow
New-NetFirewallRule -DisplayName "Allow DNS DesktopII TCP" -Direction Outbound -Protocol TCP -RemotePort 53 -Action Allow
Result:
Zero-trust outbound networking model implemented.

Phase 4 – PowerShell Remoting Complete Disablement
Primary disable command executed:
Disable-PSRemoting -Force
WinRM stopped:
Stop-Service WinRM
WinRM permanently disabled:
Set-Service WinRM -StartupType Disabled
Listeners removed:
winrm delete winrm/config/listener?Address=+Transport=HTTP
winrm delete winrm/config/listener?Address=+Transport=HTTPS
Firewall rules disabled:
Disable-NetFirewallRule -DisplayGroup "Windows Remote Management"
Validation command:
winrm quickconfig
Returned:
Not configured
Remote PowerShell execution surface fully eliminated.

Phase 5 – Network Stack Hardening
DNS manually configured to Cloudflare DNS:
1.1.1.1
1.0.0.1
DNS cache flushed:
ipconfig /flushdns
Adapter configuration validated:
ipconfig /all
NetBIOS disabled via adapter settings.
UPnP disabled via Windows Services (services.msc):
• SSDP Discovery
• UPnP Device Host

Phase 6 – Legacy Protocol Removal
SMBv1 fully removed:
Disable-WindowsOptionalFeature -Online -FeatureName SMB1Protocol -NoRestart
Result:
Legacy SMB attack surface eliminated.

Phase 7 – BIOS Reset, Update, and Security Validation
BIOS reset executed:
Load Optimized Defaults
BIOS updated using official vendor firmware via USB flash.
Security configuration verified:
• Secure Boot enabled
• TPM 2.0 enabled
• CSM disabled
• Above 4G decoding enabled
• Resize BAR enabled
Firmware integrity validated using CHIPSEC.
Installed Python:
winget install Python.Python.3
Installed CHIPSEC:
git clone https://github.com/chipsec/chipsec.git
python setup.py install
Firmware validation executed:
python chipsec_main.py -m tools.uefi.whitelist
Result:
No firmware tampering detected.

Phase 8 – Router Infrastructure Migration (Shared with Incident Response)
Previous router removed.
New router configured with hardened baseline:
• Firmware updated
• Administrator credentials changed
• Remote management disabled
• UPnP disabled
• WPA3 enabled
• WPS disabled
• No port forwarding enabled

